fields.author: Toei Animation
fields.title: One Piece
fields.description:
Gol D. Roger was known as the "Pirate King," the strongest and most infamous being to have sailed the Grand Line. The capture and execution of Roger by the World Government brought a change throughout the world. His last words before his death revealed the existence of the greatest treasure in the world, One Piece. It was this revelation that brought about the Grand Age of Pirates, men who dreamed of finding One Piece—which promises an unlimited amount of riches and fame—and quite possibly the pinnacle of glory and the title of the Pirate King.

Enter Monkey D. Luffy, a 17-year-old boy who defies your standard definition of a pirate. Rather than the popular persona of a wicked, hardened, toothless pirate ransacking villages for fun, Luffy’s reason for being a pirate is one of pure wonder: the thought of an exciting adventure that leads him to intriguing people and ultimately, the promised treasure. Following in the footsteps of his childhood hero, Luffy and his crew travel across the Grand Line, experiencing crazy adventures, unveiling dark mysteries and battling strong enemies, all in order to reach the most coveted of all fortunes—One Piece.

fields.author: Horikoshi Kouhei
fields.title: Boku No Hero Academia
fields.description: Izuku has dreamt of being a hero all his life—a lofty goal for anyone, but especially challenging for a kid with no superpowers. That’s right, in a world where eighty percent of the population has some kind of super-powered “quirk,” Izuku was unlucky enough to be born completely normal. But that’s not going to stop him from enrolling in one of the world’s most prestigious hero academies. Now, the only thing standing between him and his first class is the academy’s formidable entrance exam—nothing a little private tutoring from the world’s mightiest hero can’t solve.

fields.author: Miura Kentaro
fields.title: Berserk
fields.description: Berserk Manga is a Japanese dark fantasy manga series illustrated and written by Kentaro Miura. Place in a medieval Europe-divine the narrative centers on the characters of Guts dark fantasy world, a lone mercenary, and Griffith, the leader of a mercenary group known as the Band of the Hawk. Motifs of camaraderie, isolation, as well as the question of whether mankind is basically good or bad pervade the narrative, as it investigates both the very best and worst of human nature. Both anime and the manga are noticed for their utilization of sexual content and heavy violence.

fields.description: The story revolves around Nishimiya Shōko, a grade school student who has impaired hearing. She transfers into a new school, where she is bullied by her classmates, especially Ishida Shouya. It gets to the point where she transfers to another school and as a result, Shōya is ostracized and bullied himself, with no friends to speak of and no plans for the future. Years later, he sets himself on a path to redemption.

fields.moment:
Consistency: This series does a very good job with consistency. Moments in these series all manage to generate hype and excitement in a reader and as the series progresses, the author gets better with these moments.

Predictability: A lot of moments in this series are predictable. But, this is not really the fault of the writer. The predictability occurs because the main character is overpowered and a major plot line of this series is based around his overwhelming strength. Hence, fights and all other kinds of confrontations almost always end in his favor.

Effort: The author definitely put a lot of effort into setting up these moments and it really shows. Very rarely will a reader feel underwhelmed or feel that the moment had an unsatisfactory conclusion

Presentation: The presentation of these moments are definitely top notch, the setup, execution and conclusion are all done really well and the art only makes it better.
fields.plot:
Premise: The premise of this series is pretty underwhelming to be honest. "Zero to hero", that's a really overused plotline. It has a twist though; and thats where the uniqueness comes in. Normally, we witness as the hero gets stronger during the series but Solo Leveling is different. Within 50 chapters, he's already one of the strongest and with a few more, he eclipses all others. Because of this, the author has diverged away from the generic "underdog" plotline and has moved into something way more unique and far better all based on Sung Jin Woo's ability to "Level Up"

Pacing: The pacing is average. For the most part, the author paces the series reasonably but once in a while, the whole thing just goes out of sync just to forward the plot. A single fight could take 4 chapters while an entire month could be done in the first half of a chapter.

Complexity: The plot of this series is simple enough. It centers around the mc's ability to level up and the author has the good sense not to over-complicate it.

Immersion: This series shines in immersion. The fights and dialogues between certain characters create so much excitement in a reader. 

Realism: Well, it's a manhwa and characters in manwha tend to act smart all the time and suddenly make stupid decisions at crucial times just to forward the plot. Thankfully, solo leveling isn't like that and characters make decisions logically without going against their display characteristics.

Conclusion:

Solo Leveling is one of the best manwha out there. But, that's the thing; It's a Manwha and hence suffers from the same flaws and generic cliche as most of it's brethren. The main plot is a classic underdog story; but unlike most of it's peers, the main character peaks pretty early. So, even though he starts as the lowest of the low, he experiences exponential growth and the story quickly leaves this subplot behind. The rest o the story is then primarily driven by the suspense surrounding his mysterious powers and his ability to "Level Up" along with some of the most epic fights ever drawn.
fields.characters:
Personality: The majority of the characters in this series are cut from the same cloth — stoic and aloof. Of course, most of them are hunters and regularly put their lives on the line. But, it would have been a great improvement if there was more variety among the characters.

Chemistry: Chemistry between characters is top notch. Like I said, they are really alike so their interactions flow seamlessly. 

Backdrop:

Likability: Apart from the mc, the rest of the cast is just "meh". They evoke no emotions whatsoever in the reader. It's pretty common to get hyped over a particular character though

Development: There's little development in this series. In the early chapters, the mc does undergo some growth but go further a bit more and he just stalls. He gets more powerful, true. But, that becomes the only thing that actually changes about him.

Conclusion:

The characters are bland — painfully so. The mc is stiff and unrelatable and most of the supporting characters are more of the same. Comedy isn't really present and it's more of going from one epic fight to the next. Most of the characters are proud and overconfident and their taking down by fights or feats brings a bit of humor into the series
fields.quality: Art Quality: The art is good,and distinctive. Colors are vibrant and it's easy to interpret. It has a lot of epic panels to go along with the epic fights. Solo leveling has spawned a thousand epic wallpapers and before it's done, it will spawn a thousand more.
fields.remark: Overall, this is a very good read and one I recommend for anyone interested in manhwa. The plot isn't strong and the lack of emotion from characters don't do it any favors. But, it is something everyone should enjoy. If you just want to read as bad guys get destroyed by someone they feel is weaker than them and you want to take a break from more complex series with a bazillion subplots and just watch a full on showdown then Solo Leveling is for you.

fields.moment:
Nothing to say. It is chock full of good moments that engross you completely. The author does a good job of portraying emotion in this series and there are a lot of heartfelt moments. Action fans shouldn't despair though; there's also a lot of "demon-slaying" to keep you satisfied.

Execution: Hats off to the animators and artists on this series. The anime and manga both have perfectly executed scenes. They are really skilled at building up the suspense and excitement for a scene and then delivering said scene flawlessly. The anime outshines the manga in this regard though

Consistency: Very, very consistent. Every scene is well done and there's no drop in quality or execution

Predictability:  The majority of the scenes are predictable and plot twists are few and far between. This doesn't take away from the enjoyment in any way though. It's one thing to expect something; it's another to see it being executed flawlessly

Effort: There's so much effort put into this series(the manga and the anime). The animators and the artist gave it their 100%
fields.plot:
Premise: The premise isn't exciting. It isn't very unique as the concept of demons(vampires) and demon hunters has been done before; even the whole "revenge" thing is pretty dated. So, all in all, the premise of the series is a letdown.

Pacing: The pacing is normal. The author did a good job with this.

Complexity: The plot isn't too complex. You shouldn't have any problems following it

Immersion: This series has the ability to draw a viewer in and make you so heavily invested in it. Be warned though, it is not for the weak of heart.

Conclusion:

The plot could have been better, true. But, it's not bad enough to tarnish the image of this series.
fields.characters:
The characters are vibrant and full of life. They don't just seem like drawn people and this series will manage to evoke a lot of emotion in all but the most coldhearted of readers. The characters are varied and you will meet just about every kind of person you would expect to. The supporting characters are really good as well and do a good job, along with the main characters bring a bit of humor to the series; all while the tragic setting lurks in the background.

Personality: Top marks on this aspect. The characters are unique and all manage to establish their own identity. Of course, there are some weird characters but most of these are side characters and don't have much to do with the story.

Chemistry: The characters get along well and their relations bring smiles to the face of any reader. 

Likability: tThe characters are likable and are one of the high points of the series. This series has made a lot of profit from merchandise and that is mostly due to the likability of the characters

Development: Character development occurs throughout the series. It might not be too obvious but it does happen.
fields.quality:
Anime

Sound: This anime has really good audio. 

Voice Acting: Do yourself a favor and watch with Japanese Audio. It's really good.

Animation Quality: The animation quality is really good; this is a major reason for the popularity of the anime.

Manga

Art style:The art style is good enough. Not the best out there but far from the worst.

Communication: Understanding the panels is not an ardous task.
fields.remark: It is no surprise that this particular series won awards as well as gained a massive following. It is a testament to show that execution sometimes is enough to balance out a lacklustre plot. This is a must read/watch. You won't regret it.

fields.moment: This series is full of beautiful moments. Unfortunately, I cannot go into details without spoiling but I assure you that you won't be disappointed. There are a lot of dry spells and the arcs do not maintain the same tempo.
fields.plot: The plot of this series is sound and the progression is laudable. We experience the main character (as well as some supporting characters) grow as the series progresses. It is influenced by a lot of superhero tropes(arch nemesis, mentors, lack of self-preservation). A bunch of subplots are introduced as the series progresses and there are no jarring plotholes as of yet but that's it; nothing bad but noting exceptional either.
fields.characters: Character development is a major part of this series. The author introduces the majority of the cast in the first few chapters and from there, we just watch them develop along with the rest of the series. The characters are lively; and although there is not really much depth to them, you may still grow to love them. The main character himself is a typical shounen hero, underpowered at first but with his "never give up attitude" finds a way to come out on top. An overused trope? True. But, executed well in this case
fields.quality: The art is good. The anime art feels a lot cleaner compared to the manga. The author usually tries to show too much of what is going on and everything later ends up a splotchy mess. With the anime though, the animators did a really good job and everything is crisp and clean; especially those fight scenes we love so much
fields.remark: Overall, Boku no hero Academia is a nice read/watch. It is not one of the best anime ever made, but it certainly is one of the good ones that I'll recommend to anyone interested in anime. The quirks, the school setting and most especially the relationships between characters are truly its selling point.

fields.moment: This anime is funny, ridiculously so. That's to be expected though, seeing as it is a gag series. There are moments that will have you howling with laughter and at the same time, moments that get you revved up. One punch man is the perfect mix of both; comedy and action, hand in hand. Just avoid Tatsumaki :)
fields.plot: An anime with the most unique of plots. No zero to hero story here, no years of training to become the strongest; nothing like that. Just a guy, who from the very first episode is already the strongest in the world. The author went against the norm and in the process created one of the best manga ever made.
fields.characters: The characters are good, very few stand out as exceptional but they perform their role well. Most of the characters are flat and we're supplied with precious few information about them. The only character we might emotionally connect with; even a little bit is Mumen Rider and Saitama himself(Hair loss can be painful). The characters fit in well enough with the comedic undertones and it's always satisfying when Saitama knocks out a villain delivering a 7-minute monologue.
fields.quality:
One punch man was originally released as a webtoon and the art is horrible. Downright horrible. Thankfully, it got licensed and was redrawn. The redrawn art is really good. People and landscapes come out well and continuity across panels is good.

——————————— Anime
The animation studios did a good job. Sound, Animation, Color. Everything checks out. The season one animation was especially praised.
fields.remark: Overall, One punch man is a very good anime with loads of comedic moments. It's best if you accept early on that it's a gag anime though; otherwise, you might get irked by how easy his fights are. For it's unique plot and adventuring into an area that few authors do, it deserves an S rating

fields.moment: There are a lot of exaggerated moments and actions. But, this is understandable as battles in this series are ones of wit and intellect. Scenes with actual action are few and sparse between. This does not mean that the scenes are any less intense than actual fight scenes. The sight of minds far smarter than ours outplaying and countering each other is truly a beautiful thing to behold
fields.plot:
No man should be God. That's the single most important phrase driving this beautiful series. A genius; suddenly gifted with the ability to fix society by removing all those who would harm it. But, should this amount of power be wielded by any man? If for the sake of justice, you go against the very laws that should uphold justice. Are you still right? Are you still just? or have you become God?
Watch Death note, 10/10 for plot and story.
fields.characters: This is more of a mixed bag. On one hand, there are good characters adding flair to the series. On the other, there are extremely bad characters that do absolutely nothing with the series. One major gripe I have with it is that the women are portrayed as being extremely dumb. Not just dumb, extremely dumb and apart from Light and L, everyone else just seems a tad slower. Surprisingly, the worst character in this series is Light himself(Okay, either Light or *cough* Misa *cough*). He is a terribly flat character, and from the very first episode, there is zero character development on his part. The same goes for L, he and Light are basically carbon copies, just on opposite sides of the same conflicts. They performed wonderfully well as main characters but unfortunately, they could have been written better.
fields.quality: The art is "meh", especially the anime. It was released in 2006 and animation styles have gotten far better since then. It is not really a big issue and once you are a few episodes in; you will forget entirely about it as the story pulls you in.
fields.remark: To be honest, death note has many flaws. It could have been done better, characters could have been fleshed out better. But, all these flaws don't take away from the greatness of this series. It is one of those series, the ones that make anime stand out from other forms of media. The uniqueness of the plot garnered millions of fans for anime from across the world and that is why Death Note has earned its spot, in the Kami category

fields.moment: There are some deeply emotional moments as well as adequate buildup and execution of powerful scenes. Okay, forget all this. Just watch it.
fields.plot:
In an alchemical ritual gone wrong, Edward Elric lost his arm and his leg, and his brother Alphonse became nothing but a soul in a suit of armor. Equipped with mechanical "auto-mail" limbs, Edward becomes a state alchemist, seeking the one thing that can restore his brother and himself... the legendary Philosopher's Stone.
Yes, this is an exact copy of the description. I can't tell you about the plot but it's good; extremely good.
fields.characters:
You're still here????
Watch it already.
fields.quality: The Art is dated, for both the manga and the anime. I'd advise you to watch brotherhood instead of the original. There are few differences and brotherhood is a better version in every way
fields.remark: Fullmetal Alchemist is one of the best anime ever created. It managed to merge so many genres, so many plot-lines, so many experiences into one series with some of the best storytelling I've ever seen.

fields.moment: Nothing too fancy, nothing too bad. The moments in this story were mostly average with a few highs and also a few lows which kinda balances out at the end.
fields.plot: If you're into character-driven stories with imperfect characters who try to atone, and moments that will make you ugly cry, then you will enjoy this. The movie adaptation didn't have enough time to go into some characters' motivations and in the manga, there are a bunch of useless subplots that don't really influence the story in any way but it all ties in nicely; and the ending; especially if you watch the anime might just have you bawling like a baby.

fields.characters: No other anime/manga/manwha has a cast as varied and a culture as rich as Tower of God (with the possible exception of one piece). From the beginning, we're presented with the idea of a giant tower with each floor as big as Asia, we are then given a cast from different cultures and backgrounds, with different motivations and appearances. We meet the families, whom all have a trait unique to them. We meet the good guys, the bad guys and the thousands of people just trying to surivive. We are also presented with the relationship dynamics between Rachel and Bam; between Bam and Khun *cough* Hunter x Hunter *cough*. All in all, the cast and characters of this series are rich and diverse and rarely a chapter passes without someone new being introduced.
fields.quality: The art is good, surprisingly so. This is the author's first manwha and it shows. The first 20 chapters have very mediocre art but after that, the quality improves a ton and not long after, it matures and can now compete with the best.
fields.remark: Tower of God is hands down the best manwha around right now. The strong plot, interesting characters, compelling suspense; the author has done a really good job. The anime only has 12 episodes right now. But, the manga has gone a whole lot further; since the art is clean and the manga has no obvious artistic flaws, I'd advise you to read the manga while we wait for the anime to catch up

fields.plot: The plot is bonkers. But, it's more for laughs and an interesting experience than actual plot. The series does a good enough job of introducing just enough suspense to make us read the next chapter/episode. The plot is unpredictable and that's part of the allure.
fields.characters: The characters are bland and plain. Rimuru is the one shred of light on an otherwise barren series.
fields.quality: The art is good, for both the manga and anime. It's relatively new; so no outdated styles of animation here.
fields.remark: That time I got reincarnated as a slime is truly an interesting read/watch. It's full of humor and wacky characters and is sure to bring a smile to your face. It's still an anime though and there are some truly heartbreaking scenes scattered here and there

fields.moment: In this category, GOH truly shines. It is rife full with captivating moments and beautifully drawn action scenes. The author did a very good job with setup, execution and finishing of moments in this series. The ridiculously overpowered also help with this aspect; when a certain character(name withheld) says "Ryui Jingu, grow", You're screaming before you even realize it.
fields.plot: This is a weak point for this series. The plot seems unstable and changes at the author's whims. The author tries to establish a recurring plotline but goes about it a roundabout way and with that, introduces new plotlines that when they've served their purpose are suddenly cut off. At the end, it just seems like the plot is secondary to the action and the author just writes whatever is best to set up the next fight .
fields.characters: Like its sibling manwhas, The God of highschool has a lot of characters and it actually does a really good job of fleshing out the important ones. Unfortunately, the plot doesn't do any favors and they often perform actions against their character. Once again, this is an aspect that suffers from the author being so focused on setting up the next fight
fields.quality: The art quality is good. Action scenes are done well enough and the author expresses humor through the art well.
fields.remark: God of highschool is good, but not the best. It's good action scenes and art quality are just not enough to overlook the shabby plot and stupid characters. It actually starts off really good and the promise of the series is evident early on. A few arcs in though and the plot is in full train wreck mode. If you hate overpowered characters, a thousand plot holes, little character development, zero humor, just battle after battle. Then, this is not the series for you.
